North Korea rejects unilateral disarmament without trust
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions deepened its distrust of the United States and that the country would not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under these circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Organization’s annual General Assembly last year that North Korea had taken “essential measures out of goodwill” last year, for example, stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site, and committing not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technologies.
"We do not see a corresponding response from the United States," he said.
“Without trust in the U.S., there is no trust in our national security, and in these circumstances, we will by no means unilaterally disarm first.”
While Ri relied on North Korean complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phase-by-phase” approach to denuclearization, in which North Korea was rewarded for successive steps, his statement seemed significant in that it did not reject unilateral denuclearization from the outset, as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a sitting US president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, in which Kim had pledged to work towards “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump pledged guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea is seeking an official end to the 1950-1953 Korean War, while the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington also opposes calls for a easing of strict international sanctions against North Korea.
"The U.S. insists on 'first denuclearization' and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal through coercion, and is even opposed to the 'declaration of the end of the war,'" Ri said.
“The assumption that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a figment of the imagination of those who know nothing about us.
The problem, however, is that the continued sanctions deepen our mistrust."
Ri did not elaborate on plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US head of state had highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korea’s head of state Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea were the other party on the denuclearization issue instead of the US, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not have come to this halt.”
Nevertheless, the tone of Ri’s speech was vastly different from his speech last year when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to target the US mainland with North Korea’s missiles after “evil President” Trump referred to Kim as a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
This year, Trump, who had threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea last year, showered praise on Kim at the United Nations for his courage in taking disarmament steps, but he said there was a lot of work to be done and that the sanctions would have to remain in place until North Korea was denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no time frame for it: “Whether it takes two years, three years, or five months – it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council must reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The enforcement of the Security Council’s sanctions must in any case continue vigorously until we achieve complete, final and verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously stepped up sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to financially dry up Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and subsequently said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip has not been successful.
In July, he said on departure from Pyongyang that progress had been made, only to be accused hours later by North Korea of having made “gangster-like demands.”
North Korea vowed this month at a meeting with Moon to dismantle a missile base and nuclear complex if the United States took “appropriate action.”
He said Kim had told him that the targeted “appropriate measures” were security guarantees Trump had given in Singapore, as well as steps to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students learn in a course to get enough sleep
A new course at Harvard University ensures that all undergraduate students get more sleep this year. This is a measure against the spreading macho culture of staying awake with caffeine and learning all night long.
One scientist has found that students at the world’s leading university are often unneeded when it comes to taking care of themselves.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, and is in his opinion the first such course in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
“In the end, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why am I only learning about this now, in my last year?’
According to her, no one had ever told her how important sleep is, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
This year’s first course explained to students how the basics of good sleep habits contribute to academic and athletic performance, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after finding that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In a section, students see a picture of a room in a dorm and click on coffee cups, curtains, training shoes, and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, the effects of lack of sleep on athletic performance, and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn that long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, and cancer.
They are then encouraged to reflect on their daily routine using a map of the university campus with interactive symbols.
“We know that it won’t change the behavior of the students right away.
But we believe they have the right to know this – just like you have the right to know how the decision to smoke affects your health,” added Professor Czeisler.
Proud of “pushing a night shift” is still common, he said, adding that modern technologies and ever-increasing pressure on students made lack of sleep a growing problem.
Ensuring good sleep should be the "secret weapon" of all students against stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said, and weight gain could be avoided, as sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode so that they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, having taken one of his courses in his first year at Harvard last year.
He said the course had opened his eyes and encouraged him to push for a university-wide course.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before they begin their studies at the competitive university.
According to Professor Czeisler's recommendation, students should set an alarm clock for bedtime and wake-up time, and be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emanating from electronic screens and LED lights, which can disrupt the circadian rhythm.
