National Trust Listens to the Secret Lives of Bats
New research is being carried out at an estate in the Scottish Highlands to show how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
The findings are hoped to provide further insights into the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study, conducted by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland, will track dwarf and mosquito bats as well as the brown long-eared and water bats at Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices are placed in key positions on the property to record the activities of the bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations using portable detectors.
A noise analysis of all recordings by experts determines the frequency of the bat calls and determines which species does what.
A map and habitat report are then created to provide a detailed picture of their behavior at the landscape level.
Rob Dewar, conservation consultant for the NTS, hopes the results will show which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This data will help determine the benefits of habitat management measures, such as the creation of meadows, and show how to preserve forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom have declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects sleeping places and leads to habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, just like flycatchers and the chemical treatment of building materials or attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated echolocation to detect insects and obstacles in their trajectory.
The NTS, responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 significant gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across Scotland, takes the bat issue very seriously.
He has 10 trained experts who regularly conduct investigations, inspections of sleeping places and sometimes rescue measures.
The organisation has even established Scotland’s first and only bat reserve at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland’s 10 bat species.
Estate manager David Thompson explains that the property is the ideal habitat for them.
“Here in Threave, we have a great area for bats,” he explains.
“We have the old buildings, many old trees and an excellent habitat.
But there’s a lot we don’t know about bats yet, so we’re doing this work here and on other goods that will help us learn more about what bats need to feel comfortable.”
He stresses the importance of first excluding the presence of bats before maintenance work in the goods, as it is possible that the involuntary destruction of a single nesting site could kill up to 400 females and juveniles and wipe out the entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or destroy them or their nesting sites.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official at the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the local community to help.
“We still have a lot to learn about bats, and many of our species we don’t know about their populations.”
