China vowed to respond to any U.S. action, and it is unlikely that the world’s second-largest economic power will soon stumble.
To persuade Washington to give in would mean to give in, but a public crackdown on the US would be far too shameful for China’s President Xi Jinping.
Nevertheless, experts believe that if Beijing plays its cards well, China could benefit from the effects of the trade war in the long term by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
"The fact that a quick political decision in either Washington or Beijing could create the conditions for economic turbulence in both countries is actually much more dangerous than many observers have previously realized," says Abigail Grace, a research associate who focuses on Asia at the Center for New American Security think tank.
Syria is 'ready' to return refugees, Foreign Minister says
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help to rebuild the country devastated by the seven-year war.
In a speech to the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said that the situation in the country is improving.
"Today, thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism, the situation on the ground is more stable and secure," he said.
The government is rebuilding the areas destroyed by terrorists to restore normalcy.
All conditions are now in place for the voluntary return of refugees to the country, which they had to leave due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian government welcomed aid in rebuilding the devastated country.
He stressed, however, that it would not accept conditional assistance from countries that had supported the uprising.
Europe won the Ryder Cup in Paris
Team Europe won the 2018 Ryder Cup, defeating Team USA with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 at Le Golf National near Paris.
The U.S. has now lost six consecutive times on European soil and has not won a Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe won the crown back after Danish captain Thomas Bjorn's team scored the 14.5 points it needed to defeat the US.
The American star Phil Mickelson, who had problems over much of the tournament, sank his tee shot on the 16th track (Par 3) in the water and lost to Francesco Molinari.
The Italian golfer Molinari was able to shine in all his rounds and became one of 4 players who scored a 5-0 since the tournament began in its current format in 1979.
American Jordan Spieth was beaten 5-4 by the lowest ranking player in Team Europe, Thorbjorn Olesen from Denmark.
The player with the world’s best ranking, Dustin Johnson, lost 2 to 1 against England’s Ian Poulter, who may have played his last Ryder Cup.
The Spaniard Sergio Garcia, veteran of eight Ryder Cups, became the best European Ryder Cup player of all time with 25.5 career points.
“Normally I don’t cry, but today I couldn’t hold back.
It was a difficult year.
I am so grateful that Thomas chose me and believed in me.
I'm so infinitely happy to win the cup back.
It’s about the team and I’m happy to have made a contribution,” said the emotional Garcia after the European victory.
He passes the torch on to his compatriot John Rahm, who won against the American golf legend Tiger Woods on Sunday 2:1 in the individual encounters.
I'm so incredibly proud to have beaten Tiger Woods, whom I've watched on TV since I was a kid," Rahm said.
Woods lost all his four games in France and now has a Ryder Cup balance of 13-21-3.
A strange statistic for one of the greatest players of all time, who has won 14 major titles and is surpassed only by Jack Nicklaus.
Team USA had trouble finding the fairways all weekend, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who have achieved top performances throughout the tournament.
American captain Jim Furyk said after a disappointing performance of his team: “I’m proud of the guys, they fought.
There was a time this morning when we put pressure on Europe.
We didn't do anything about it.
Hats off to Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All his 12 players did a good job.
We will regroup, I will talk to the PGA America and our Ryder Cup committee and we will look forward.
I love these 12 guys and I’m proud to be their captain.
You have to take off your hat.
We were defeated."
Red Tide Update: Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota Decline
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decline in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more patchy flowering conditions are recorded in the areas of the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, indicating declining concentrations.
A red algal bloom extends over approximately 130 miles of coastline from Pinellas north to the south of Lee County.
Spots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places compared to the previous week.
A red tide was also observed in the Pasco district.
Last week, mean concentrations were reported in or off the coast of Pinellas County, low to high concentrations off the coast of Manatee County, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of Charlotte County, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
Respiratory complaints continue to be reported from the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No new respiratory problems have been reported in Northwestern Florida over the past week.
